1
00:00:55,639 --> 00:00:58,767
There are some fish
that cannot be caught.

2
00:01:00,644 --> 00:01:03,689
It's not that they're faster
or stronger than other fish.

3
00:01:04,147 --> 00:01:07,276
They're just touched
by something extra.

4
00:01:08,652 --> 00:01:11,321
One such fish was The Beast.

5
00:01:12,656 --> 00:01:16,660
And by the time I was born
he was already a legend.

6
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:21,623
He'd passed up more $ 100 lures
than any fish in Alabama.

7
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:25,586
Some said that fish was
the ghost of a thief...

8
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:29,006
...who'd drowned in that river
60 years before.

9
00:01:30,674 --> 00:01:35,387
Others claimed he was a dinosaur
left over from the "Cruaceous" Period.

10
00:01:35,679 --> 00:01:39,516
I didn't put any stock into
such speculation or superstition.

11
00:01:39,683 --> 00:01:42,436
All I knew was I'd been trying
to catch that fish...

12
00:01:42,686 --> 00:01:45,272
...since I was a boy
no bigger than you.

13
00:01:45,689 --> 00:01:48,192
And on the day you were born...

14
00:01:48,192 --> 00:01:51,153
Well, that was the day
I finally caught him.

15
00:01:53,697 --> 00:01:54,698
Now, I'd tried everything on it:

16
00:01:55,199 --> 00:01:58,827
Worms, lures, peanut butter,
peanut butter and cheese.

17
00:01:59,203 --> 00:02:01,663
But on that day I had a revelation:

18
00:02:01,705 --> 00:02:06,543
If that fish was Henry Walls' ghost,
then the usual bait wasn't gonna work.

19
00:02:06,710 --> 00:02:11,340
I was gonna have to use something
he truly desired.

20
00:02:12,216 --> 00:02:14,718
- Your finger?
- Gold.

21
00:02:15,219 --> 00:02:18,388
Now, I tied my ring onto
the strongest line they made...

22
00:02:18,722 --> 00:02:23,560
...strong enough to hold up a bridge,
they said, if only for a few minutes.

23
00:02:24,228 --> 00:02:26,855
And then I cast upriver.

24
00:02:29,733 --> 00:02:34,363
The Beast jumped up and grabbed it
before it even hit the water.

25
00:02:34,738 --> 00:02:39,284
And just as fast,
he snapped clean through that line.

26
00:02:39,243 --> 00:02:40,786
Well, you can see my predicament.

27
00:02:41,245 --> 00:02:45,207
My wedding ring,
the symbol of fidelity to my wife...

28
00:02:45,249 --> 00:02:47,793
...soon to be mother of my child...
- Make him stop.

29
00:02:48,252 --> 00:02:50,671
...was now lost in the gut
of an uncatchable fish.

30
00:02:51,255 --> 00:02:52,589
What did you do?

31
00:02:53,257 --> 00:02:56,426
I followed that fish upriver
and downriver.

32
00:02:58,262 --> 00:03:00,556
This fish, The Beast...

33
00:03:00,764 --> 00:03:06,687
...the whole time we were calling it
a him, when in fact it was a her.

34
00:03:06,770 --> 00:03:09,189
It was fat with eggs
it was gonna lay any day.

35
00:03:09,273 --> 00:03:11,775
Now, I was in a situation.

36
00:03:12,276 --> 00:03:15,737
I could gut that fish
and get my wedding ring back...

37
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:21,243
...but in doing so I'd be killing the
smartest catfish in the Ashton River.

38
00:03:21,285 --> 00:03:23,579
Did I want to deprive
my son the chance...

39
00:03:23,787 --> 00:03:26,790
...to catch a fish like this
of his own?

40
00:03:27,791 --> 00:03:29,626
This ladyfish and I...

41
00:03:29,793 --> 00:03:34,339
- Well, we had the same destiny.
- "We were part of the same equation."

42
00:03:35,299 --> 00:03:37,342
Now, you may well ask...

43
00:03:37,801 --> 00:03:41,555
Oh, darling, darling,
it's still your night.

44
00:03:41,805 --> 00:03:47,686
...why did it strike so quick on gold
when nothing else would attract it?

45
00:03:47,811 --> 00:03:50,898
That was the lesson
I learned that day...

46
00:03:50,814 --> 00:03:53,817
...the day my son was born.

47
00:03:54,318 --> 00:04:00,324
Sometimes the only way to catch
an uncatchable woman...

48
00:04:00,324 --> 00:04:03,744
...is to offer her a wedding ring.

49
00:04:12,336 --> 00:04:15,088
What, a father's not allowed
to talk about his son?

50
00:04:15,339 --> 00:04:17,174
I'm a footnote in that story, Dad...

51
00:04:17,341 --> 00:04:23,430
...the context for your great adventure,
which never happened, incidentally.

52
00:04:23,347 --> 00:04:26,433
You were selling novelty products
in Wichita when I was born.

53
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:29,478
Come on, Will.
Everyone loves that story!

54
00:04:29,353 --> 00:04:33,649
They don't. I don't love that story. Not
anymore. Not after a thousand times!

55
00:04:33,857 --> 00:04:37,778
I know every punch line, Dad.
I can tell them as well as you can!

56
00:04:38,862 --> 00:04:41,448
For one night,
one night in your entire life...

57
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:44,952
...the universe did not revolve
around Edward Bloom.

58
00:04:44,868 --> 00:04:49,373
- How can you not understand that?
- I'm sorry to embarrass you.

59
00:04:49,373 --> 00:04:53,252
You're embarrassing yourself, Dad.
You just don't see it.

60
00:04:55,379 --> 00:04:59,383
After that night, I didn't speak
to my father again for three years.

61
00:05:04,888 --> 00:05:08,851
William Bloom, United Press
International. If I could just...

62
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:15,649
We communicated indirectly, I guess.

63
00:05:15,399 --> 00:05:19,361
In her letters and Christmas cards,
my mother wrote for both of them.

64
00:05:19,903 --> 00:05:24,825
And when I'd call, she'd say Dad was
out driving or swimming in the pool.

65
00:05:24,908 --> 00:05:27,911
True to form, we never
talked about not talking.

66
00:05:30,914 --> 00:05:34,626
The truth is, I didn't see anything
of myself in my father.

67
00:05:34,918 --> 00:05:38,172
And I don't think he saw anything
of himself in me.

68
00:05:41,925 --> 00:05:46,054
We were like strangers
who knew each other very well.

69
00:05:50,434 --> 00:05:52,686
In telling the story
of my father's life...

70
00:05:52,936 --> 00:05:57,482
...it's impossible to separate fact
from fiction, the man from the myth.

71
00:06:00,944 --> 00:06:03,947
The best I can do
is to tell it the way he told me.

72
00:06:05,949 --> 00:06:09,703
It doesn't always make sense,
and most of it never happened.

73
00:06:34,978 --> 00:06:36,980
Give me back my ring!

74
00:06:49,993 --> 00:06:50,911
Thank you!

75
00:06:51,495 --> 00:06:54,623
But that's what kind of story this is.

76
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:06,718
His birth would set the pace
for his unlikely life.

77
00:07:07,010 --> 00:07:10,013
No longer than most men's,
but larger.

78
00:07:10,013 --> 00:07:12,474
And as strange as his stories got...

79
00:07:12,516 --> 00:07:15,936
...the endings were always
the most surprising of all.

80
00:07:43,046 --> 00:07:45,841
Yes. Yes, he's here.

81
00:07:46,550 --> 00:07:48,343
It's your mother.

82
00:07:55,559 --> 00:07:57,978
And what does Dr. Bennett say?

83
00:07:59,563 --> 00:08:01,440
No, sure, I'll talk to him.

84
00:08:02,566 --> 00:08:04,526
Yeah, I'll wait.

85
00:08:05,068 --> 00:08:06,653
It's bad?

86
00:08:06,570 --> 00:08:10,616
Yeah, it's more than they thought.
They're gonna stop chemo.

87
00:08:11,575 --> 00:08:14,286
- You need to go.
- Probably tonight.

88
00:08:15,579 --> 00:08:18,665
- I'm going with you.
- No, no, no. You shouldn't.

89
00:08:19,082 --> 00:08:20,876
I'm going with you.

90
00:08:50,113 --> 00:08:51,949
Now, which one's it gonna be?

91
00:08:52,115 --> 00:08:54,993
"Monkey in a Barn,"
or "Dog in the Road"?

92
00:08:55,369 --> 00:08:56,036
The one about the witch.

93
00:08:55,619 --> 00:08:56,995
The one about the witch.

94
00:09:00,624 --> 00:09:04,253
- You get nightmares.
- But I'm not scared.

95
00:09:06,129 --> 00:09:08,715
Well, neither was I, at first.

96
00:09:09,132 --> 00:09:12,052
Now, this took place
in the swamp outside of Ashton.

97
00:09:12,135 --> 00:09:16,807
Children weren't allowed in the swamp
on account of the snakes, spiders...

98
00:09:17,140 --> 00:09:21,770
...and quicksand that would swallow
you up before you could even scream.

99
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:24,273
There were five of us
out there that night:

100
00:09:24,648 --> 00:09:27,943
Me, Ruthie, Wilbur Freely...

101
00:09:28,151 --> 00:09:31,822
...and the Price Brothers,
Don and Zacky.

102
00:09:32,155 --> 00:09:35,951
And not one of us knew
what was in store.

103
00:09:36,660 --> 00:09:40,789
It's common knowledge that most
towns of a certain size have a witch...

104
00:09:41,164 --> 00:09:43,292
...if only to eat
misbehaving children...

105
00:09:43,166 --> 00:09:46,628
...and the occasional puppy
who wanders into her yard.

106
00:09:46,670 --> 00:09:49,756
Witches use those bones
to cast spells and curses...

107
00:09:50,174 --> 00:09:52,676
...and make the land infertile.

108
00:09:52,676 --> 00:09:56,763
- Is it true she got a glass eye?
- I heard she got it from gypsies.

109
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:58,807
- What's a gypsy?
- Your momma's a gypsy.

110
00:09:59,183 --> 00:10:00,601
Your momma's a bitch.

111
00:10:00,684 --> 00:10:02,853
You shouldn't swear.
There's ladies present.

112
00:10:03,187 --> 00:10:04,354
- Shit.
- Damn.

113
00:10:05,189 --> 00:10:05,689
Screw.

114
00:10:05,689 --> 00:10:07,733
Turn off your flashlights.
She'll see you!

115
00:10:08,192 --> 00:10:10,861
Yet of all the witches in Alabama...

116
00:10:10,694 --> 00:10:13,614
...there was one who was said
to be the most feared.

117
00:10:13,697 --> 00:10:17,743
For she had one glass eye which
was said to contain mystical powers.

118
00:10:18,202 --> 00:10:22,039
I heard if you look right at it,
you'll see how you're gonna die.

119
00:10:22,206 --> 00:10:25,918
That's bull-S-H-l-T, that is.
She's not even a real witch.

120
00:10:26,210 --> 00:10:28,253
If you're so sure, go get that eye.

121
00:10:28,212 --> 00:10:32,841
I heard she keeps it in a box on her
night table. Or are you too scared?

122
00:10:33,217 --> 00:10:35,344
I'll go in right now and get that eye.

123
00:10:35,719 --> 00:10:37,846
- Then do it.
- Fine, I will.

124
00:10:37,721 --> 00:10:40,641
- Fine, you do it.
- Fine, I'm doing it.

125
00:10:40,724 --> 00:10:42,893
Edward, don't!

126
00:10:43,227 --> 00:10:47,189
She'll make soap out of you.
That's what she does.

127
00:10:47,231 --> 00:10:49,900
She makes soap out of people.

128
00:11:39,783 --> 00:11:42,035
Ma'am, my name is Edward Bloom...

129
00:11:42,286 --> 00:11:44,955
...and there's some folks
like to see your eye.

130
00:11:58,302 --> 00:12:00,262
- You get The Eye?
- I brought it.

131
00:12:00,304 --> 00:12:01,388
Let's see it.

132
00:12:07,311 --> 00:12:09,188
Whoa, help!

133
00:12:18,822 --> 00:12:22,993
I saw how I was gonna die.
I was old and I fell.

134
00:12:23,827 --> 00:12:26,163
I wasn't old at all.

135
00:12:33,837 --> 00:12:37,132
I was thinking about death and all.
About seeing how you're gonna die.

136
00:12:37,841 --> 00:12:41,178
I mean, on one hand,
if dying was all you thought about...

137
00:12:41,345 --> 00:12:43,096
...it could kind of screw you up.

138
00:12:43,347 --> 00:12:47,100
But it could kind of help you,
couldn't it?

139
00:12:47,351 --> 00:12:51,396
Because, everything else,
you'd know you could survive.

140
00:12:53,857 --> 00:12:56,902
I guess I'm saying I'd like to know.

141
00:13:08,872 --> 00:13:10,874
That's how I go.

142
00:13:33,397 --> 00:13:34,481
Hi, Mom.

143
00:13:40,404 --> 00:13:45,492
- Is that Dr. Bennett's car?
- Yes. He's up with your father now.

144
00:13:45,909 --> 00:13:49,288
- And how is he?
- Well... No, I got it.

145
00:13:49,413 --> 00:13:53,417
He's impossible. He won't eat.
Because he doesn't eat, he's weaker.

146
00:13:53,917 --> 00:13:55,961
Because he's weak,
he doesn't want to eat.

147
00:13:55,919 --> 00:14:00,799
- How much time does he have left?
- You don't talk about that.

148
00:14:01,425 --> 00:14:03,927
Not yet.

149
00:14:04,428 --> 00:14:06,013
Will.

150
00:14:06,930 --> 00:14:09,933
Dr. Bennett. Oh, it's good to see you.

151
00:14:10,434 --> 00:14:13,729
My wife, Josephine.

152
00:14:13,937 --> 00:14:15,189
A pleasure.

153
00:14:16,440 --> 00:14:19,401
- You're seven months.
- To the day!

154
00:14:21,445 --> 00:14:22,613
It's a boy.

155
00:14:25,449 --> 00:14:31,079
Try to get him to drink one of these.
He won't, but go ahead and try.

156
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:18,168
Dad?

157
00:15:29,513 --> 00:15:31,932
You want some water?

158
00:15:48,532 --> 00:15:52,494
- You are in for a surprise.
- Am I?

159
00:15:52,536 --> 00:15:55,330
Having a kid changes everything.

160
00:15:55,539 --> 00:15:59,334
There's the diapers and the burping
and the midnight feeding.

161
00:15:59,543 --> 00:16:02,546
- Did you do any of that?
- No.

162
00:16:03,547 --> 00:16:05,549
But I hear it's terrible.

163
00:16:06,049 --> 00:16:11,221
Then you spend years trying
to corrupt and mislead this child...

164
00:16:11,054 --> 00:16:16,101
...fill its head with nonsense,
and still it turns out perfectly fine.

165
00:16:16,560 --> 00:16:21,190
- You think I'm up for it?
- You learned from the best.

166
00:16:25,068 --> 00:16:27,487
Drink half the can.
I'll tell Mom you drank it all.

167
00:16:28,071 --> 00:16:29,531
Everyone wins.

168
00:16:30,073 --> 00:16:33,994
People needn't worry so much.
It's not my time yet.

169
00:16:34,077 --> 00:16:36,038
This is not how I go.

170
00:16:36,079 --> 00:16:40,209
- Really?
- Truly. I saw it in The Eye.

171
00:16:41,084 --> 00:16:44,379
- The old lady by the swamp?
- She was a witch.

172
00:16:44,588 --> 00:16:47,257
No, she was old and probably senile.

173
00:16:47,591 --> 00:16:52,721
I saw my death in that eye,
and this isn't how it happens.

174
00:16:52,596 --> 00:16:54,806
So how does it happen?

175
00:16:55,098 --> 00:16:59,520
Surprise ending.
Wouldn't want to ruin it for you.

176
00:17:00,604 --> 00:17:03,440
Your mother thought
we wouldn't talk again.

177
00:17:03,607 --> 00:17:06,401
Look at us. We're talking fine.

178
00:17:06,610 --> 00:17:08,445
We're storytellers, both of us.

179
00:17:08,612 --> 00:17:14,159
I speak mine out,
you write yours down. Same thing.

180
00:17:15,619 --> 00:17:17,287
Dad...

181
00:17:20,123 --> 00:17:22,626
I hope to talk about some things
while I'm here.

182
00:17:23,627 --> 00:17:25,254
You mean while I'm here.

183
00:17:25,629 --> 00:17:29,383
I just want to know
the true versions of things:

184
00:17:29,633 --> 00:17:32,427
Events. Stories.

185
00:17:32,636 --> 00:17:33,971
You.

186
00:17:45,649 --> 00:17:48,277
Your mother hasn't been
keeping up the pool.

187
00:17:48,151 --> 00:17:51,989
- lf you wanted to, you could fix it.
- Yeah, I will.

188
00:17:52,155 --> 00:17:55,284
- You know where the chemicals are?
- I did it when you were gone.

189
00:17:55,659 --> 00:18:01,623
I was never much for being
at home, Will. Too confining.

190
00:18:02,165 --> 00:18:04,710
And this here, being stuck in bed...

191
00:18:05,169 --> 00:18:08,547
Dying is the worst thing
that's ever happened to me.

192
00:18:09,673 --> 00:18:15,387
- I thought you said you weren't dying.
- I said this isn't how I go.

193
00:18:15,179 --> 00:18:19,099
The last part is much more unusual.

194
00:18:19,683 --> 00:18:21,935
Trust me on that.

195
00:18:54,718 --> 00:18:57,679
Dr. Bennett said I have
to stay at home for a week.

196
00:18:57,721 --> 00:19:01,433
Oh, that's nothing. Once,
I had to stay in bed for three years.

197
00:19:01,725 --> 00:19:04,895
- Did you have the chickenpox?
- I wish.

198
00:19:24,248 --> 00:19:27,000
Truth is, no one quite knew
what was wrong.

199
00:19:27,251 --> 00:19:29,628
Most times a person
grows up gradually...

200
00:19:30,254 --> 00:19:32,548
...while I found myself in a hurry.

201
00:19:35,759 --> 00:19:39,888
My muscles and my bones couldn't
keep up with my body's ambition.

202
00:19:40,264 --> 00:19:43,308
So I spent the better part
of three years confined to my bed...

203
00:19:43,767 --> 00:19:47,688
...with the encyclopedia being
my only means of exploration.

204
00:19:47,771 --> 00:19:49,773
I had made it all the way to the G's...

205
00:19:50,274 --> 00:19:52,943
...hoping to find an answer
to my "gigantificationism"...

206
00:19:53,777 --> 00:19:56,864
...when I uncovered an article
about the common goldfish.

207
00:19:57,281 --> 00:20:00,701
"Kept in a small bowl,
the goldfish will remain small.

208
00:20:01,285 --> 00:20:02,536
With more space...

209
00:20:02,786 --> 00:20:06,623
...the fish will grow double, triple,
or quadruple its size."

210
00:20:06,790 --> 00:20:10,002
It occurred to me then that perhaps
the reason for my growth...

211
00:20:10,294 --> 00:20:12,421
...was that I was intended
for larger things.

212
00:20:12,796 --> 00:20:16,383
After all, a giant man can't have
an ordinary-sized life.

213
00:20:17,801 --> 00:20:21,180
As soon as my bones had settled
in their adult configuration...

214
00:20:21,305 --> 00:20:26,268
...I set upon my plan to make
a bigger place for myself in Ashton.

215
00:20:26,310 --> 00:20:27,477
Tigers, go!

216
00:20:43,327 --> 00:20:44,912
Edward Bloom!

217
00:21:27,871 --> 00:21:31,875
Doggy! My doggy!
My doggy's trapped!

218
00:21:40,884 --> 00:21:43,887
I was the biggest thing
Ashton had ever seen.

219
00:21:44,888 --> 00:21:47,891
Until one day, a stranger arrived.

220
00:22:02,906 --> 00:22:07,578
Calm down. Calm down, everybody.
Calm down. That's enough.

221
00:22:07,911 --> 00:22:11,707
- Mr. Mayor, he ate an entire corn field.
- He ate my dog.

222
00:22:11,915 --> 00:22:14,543
If you ain't gonna stop him, mayor,
we will.

223
00:22:14,418 --> 00:22:17,421
I won't have mob violence
in this town.

224
00:22:17,921 --> 00:22:19,840
Now, has someone tried
talking to him?

225
00:22:19,923 --> 00:22:22,593
- You can't reason with him.
- He's a monster.

226
00:22:22,926 --> 00:22:24,636
I'll do it.

227
00:22:38,942 --> 00:22:41,361
I'll talk to him.
See if I can get him to go.

228
00:22:41,445 --> 00:22:43,739
That creature could crush you
without trying.

229
00:22:44,448 --> 00:22:47,451
Oh, trust me, he'll have to try.

230
00:23:18,482 --> 00:23:19,858
Hello?

231
00:23:24,988 --> 00:23:27,783
My name is Edward Bloom,
and I wanna talk to you!

232
00:23:28,492 --> 00:23:30,786
Go away!

233
00:23:32,996 --> 00:23:36,041
Now, I'm not going anywhere
until you show yourself!

234
00:23:35,999 --> 00:23:39,002
I said, go away!

235
00:23:59,523 --> 00:24:01,859
Armed with the foreknowledge
of my own death...

236
00:24:02,025 --> 00:24:04,111
...I knew the giant couldn't kill me.

237
00:24:06,530 --> 00:24:09,741
All the same, I preferred to keep
my bones unbroken.

238
00:24:10,033 --> 00:24:11,994
Why are you here?

239
00:24:14,037 --> 00:24:14,913
So you can eat me.

240
00:24:15,539 --> 00:24:19,293
The town decided to send
a human sacrifice and I volunteered.

241
00:24:20,043 --> 00:24:23,005
My arms are a little stringy, but
there's some good eating in my legs.

242
00:24:23,046 --> 00:24:26,884
I mean, I'd be tempted
to eat them myself.

243
00:24:28,552 --> 00:24:30,596
So I guess, well...

244
00:24:31,054 --> 00:24:35,225
If you'd just get it over with quick,
because I'm not much for pain, really.

245
00:24:47,571 --> 00:24:51,158
Oh, come on! I can't go back!
I'm a human sacrifice!

246
00:24:52,075 --> 00:24:53,952
If I go back,
they'll think I'm a coward.

247
00:24:54,077 --> 00:24:56,705
I'd rather be dinner than a coward.

248
00:24:57,581 --> 00:24:58,707
Here.

249
00:24:59,082 --> 00:25:02,127
You can start with my hand.
It'll be an appetizer.

250
00:25:02,586 --> 00:25:06,798
I don't want to eat you.
I don't want to eat anybody.

251
00:25:06,590 --> 00:25:10,636
I just get so hungry.
I'm just too big.

252
00:25:12,095 --> 00:25:14,890
Did you ever think that
maybe you're not too big...

253
00:25:15,098 --> 00:25:17,184
...but maybe this town
is just too small?

254
00:25:17,100 --> 00:25:19,978
I've heard in real cities
there are buildings so tall...

255
00:25:20,103 --> 00:25:22,439
...you can't even see
the tops of them.

256
00:25:22,606 --> 00:25:24,983
- Really?
- Oh, I wouldn't lie to you.

257
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:27,528
And all-you-can-eat buffets.

258
00:25:27,611 --> 00:25:30,572
- Now, you can eat a lot, can't you?
- I can.

259
00:25:30,614 --> 00:25:33,534
So why are you wasting your time
in a small town?

260
00:25:34,117 --> 00:25:37,162
You're a big man.
You should be in a big city.

261
00:25:37,120 --> 00:25:40,249
You're just trying to get me
to leave, aren't you?

262
00:25:40,624 --> 00:25:44,044
- What's your name, giant?
- Karl.

263
00:25:44,127 --> 00:25:47,631
Well, mine's Edward.
And truthfully...

264
00:25:48,131 --> 00:25:51,927
Well, I do want you to leave, Karl.
But I want to leave with you.

265
00:25:52,135 --> 00:25:54,930
I mean, you think this town
is too small for you?

266
00:25:55,138 --> 00:25:58,183
Well, it's too small for a man
of my ambition.

267
00:25:58,141 --> 00:26:01,270
So, what do you say? Join me?

268
00:26:04,648 --> 00:26:05,774
Okay.

269
00:26:07,150 --> 00:26:08,694
Okay.

270
00:26:08,652 --> 00:26:11,780
Now, first, we gotta
get you ready for the city.

271
00:26:28,672 --> 00:26:32,885
Edward Bloom, first son of Ashton...

272
00:26:33,177 --> 00:26:36,722
...it's with a heavy heart
that we see you go.

273
00:26:37,181 --> 00:26:39,850
But take with you
this key to the city...

274
00:26:39,683 --> 00:26:42,603
...and know that any time
you want to come back...

275
00:26:42,686 --> 00:26:45,731
...all our doors are open to you.

276
00:26:54,698 --> 00:26:58,702
That afternoon as I left Ashton,
everyone seemed to have advice.

277
00:26:58,702 --> 00:27:01,830
Find yourself a nice girl, now!

278
00:27:02,206 --> 00:27:05,209
Watch your pride, Edward Bloom!

279
00:27:05,209 --> 00:27:09,922
But there was one person whose
counsel I held above all others.

280
00:27:13,717 --> 00:27:16,303
She said that the biggest fish
in the river...

281
00:27:17,221 --> 00:27:19,848
...gets that way
by never being caught.

282
00:27:24,228 --> 00:27:27,689
- What'd she say?
- Beats me.

283
00:27:40,244 --> 00:27:41,370
There were two roads out of Ashton:

284
00:27:42,246 --> 00:27:44,623
A new one which was paved
and an older one that wasn't.

285
00:27:44,748 --> 00:27:46,750
People didn't use
the old one anymore...

286
00:27:46,750 --> 00:27:49,545
...and it had developed a reputation
for being haunted.

287
00:27:49,753 --> 00:27:52,881
Well, since I had no intention
of ever returning to Ashton...

288
00:27:53,257 --> 00:27:57,386
...this seemed as good a time as any
to find out what lay down that old one.

289
00:27:57,761 --> 00:28:02,349
- You know anyone who's taken it?
- That poet, Norther Winslow, did.

290
00:28:02,766 --> 00:28:05,143
He was going to Paris, France.

291
00:28:05,269 --> 00:28:08,772
I guess he liked it.
No one ever heard from him again.

292
00:28:09,273 --> 00:28:11,358
I'll tell you what.
You go the other way.

293
00:28:11,275 --> 00:28:14,903
I'll cut through here,
and I'll meet you on the far side.

294
00:28:16,280 --> 00:28:19,324
You're just trying to run away,
aren't you?

295
00:28:20,784 --> 00:28:21,952
Here.

296
00:28:23,287 --> 00:28:26,540
Just to be sure, you can take my pack.

297
00:29:05,829 --> 00:29:08,332
Why, you son of a...

298
00:29:34,358 --> 00:29:36,360
Now, there comes a point
when a reasonable man...

299
00:29:36,360 --> 00:29:41,156
...will swallow his pride and admit
that he's made a terrible mistake.

300
00:29:41,365 --> 00:29:46,286
The truth is,
I was never a reasonable man.

301
00:29:47,371 --> 00:29:50,082
And what I recall of
Sunday school was that...

302
00:29:50,374 --> 00:29:55,420
...the more difficult something is,
the more rewarding it is in the end.

303
00:30:54,605 --> 00:30:57,149
Friend! Welcome to you!

304
00:30:58,108 --> 00:31:01,069
- What's your name?
- Edward Bloom.

305
00:31:02,112 --> 00:31:05,115
- "Bloom" like a flower?
- Yes.

306
00:31:05,115 --> 00:31:09,161
Oh, here! Here you are, right here.
"Edward Bloom."

307
00:31:09,620 --> 00:31:11,997
We weren't expecting you yet.

308
00:31:12,122 --> 00:31:14,166
- You were expecting me?
- Not yet.

309
00:31:14,625 --> 00:31:19,254
- You must've taken a shortcut.
- Why, yes, I did. It almost killed me.

310
00:31:19,630 --> 00:31:23,675
Life will do that to you.
And truthfully, the long way is easier.

311
00:31:24,134 --> 00:31:26,970
- But it's longer.
- Much longer.

312
00:31:27,137 --> 00:31:30,015
And you're here now,
and that's what matters.

313
00:31:30,140 --> 00:31:31,266
What is this place?

314
00:31:31,642 --> 00:31:34,937
The town of Spectre.
Best-kept secret in Alabama!

315
00:31:35,145 --> 00:31:38,440
Now, it says here
you're from Ashton, right?

316
00:31:38,649 --> 00:31:42,027
Last person we had from Ashton
was Norther Winslow.

317
00:31:42,152 --> 00:31:44,071
The poet?
Whatever happened to him?

318
00:31:44,154 --> 00:31:48,408
He's still here. Let me buy you a drink.
I'll tell you all about it.

319
00:31:49,159 --> 00:31:50,369
Hell, I'll have him tell you!

320
00:31:51,161 --> 00:31:54,206
I have to meet somebody,
and I'm already running late.

321
00:31:54,164 --> 00:31:58,043
Now, son, I already told you.
You're early.

322
00:32:32,703 --> 00:32:35,747
Now, tell me if that isn't
the best pie you ever ate.

323
00:32:36,707 --> 00:32:37,666
It truly is.

324
00:32:42,212 --> 00:32:46,383
Well, everything tastes better here.
Even the water is sweet.

325
00:32:48,218 --> 00:32:51,388
Never gets too hot,
too cold, too humid.

326
00:32:52,222 --> 00:32:55,309
At night, the wind goes through
the trees where you'd swear...

327
00:32:55,726 --> 00:32:59,396
...there was a whole symphony
out there playing just for you.

328
00:33:02,232 --> 00:33:03,984
Hey! Jenny!

329
00:33:05,235 --> 00:33:06,528
Come back here!

330
00:33:12,242 --> 00:33:13,535
Jenny!

331
00:33:29,259 --> 00:33:31,011
Hey, I need those.

332
00:33:31,762 --> 00:33:35,182
- There is no softer ground than town.
- That almost rhymes.

333
00:33:35,265 --> 00:33:37,601
He's our poet laureate. Come on.

334
00:33:41,271 --> 00:33:44,650
I agreed to spend the afternoon,
if only to understand...

335
00:33:45,275 --> 00:33:49,446
...the mystery of how a place could
feel so strange and yet so familiar.

336
00:33:53,784 --> 00:33:56,370
I've been working on this poem
for 12 years.

337
00:33:56,286 --> 00:33:58,038
Really?

338
00:33:58,288 --> 00:34:03,544
There's a lot of expectation.
I don't wanna disappoint my fans.

339
00:34:03,794 --> 00:34:05,254
May I?

340
00:34:25,816 --> 00:34:27,442
It's only three lines long.

341
00:34:30,821 --> 00:34:34,116
This is why you should never show
a work in progress.

342
00:35:29,880 --> 00:35:31,840
I got him!

343
00:35:47,397 --> 00:35:49,066
There's leeches in there.

344
00:35:49,900 --> 00:35:52,861
- Did you see that woman?
- What did she look like?

345
00:35:53,403 --> 00:35:56,698
- Well, she was...
- Was she naked?

346
00:35:58,909 --> 00:36:00,452
Yes, she was.

347
00:36:00,410 --> 00:36:04,581
It's not a woman. It's a fish.
No one ever catches her.

348
00:36:05,415 --> 00:36:07,459
Fish looks different
to different people.

349
00:36:07,918 --> 00:36:11,713
My daddy said it looked like the
coon dog he had when he was a kid...

350
00:36:12,422 --> 00:36:14,466
...back from the dead.

351
00:36:17,928 --> 00:36:19,763
Oh, darn.

352
00:36:21,932 --> 00:36:24,268
- How old are you?
- Eighteen.

353
00:36:24,434 --> 00:36:28,438
I'm 8. That means when I'm 18,
you'll be 28.

354
00:36:28,438 --> 00:36:33,193
- And when I'm 28, you'll only be 38.
- You're pretty good at arithmetic.

355
00:36:33,443 --> 00:36:37,823
And when I'm 38, you'll be 48.
That's not much difference at all.

356
00:36:37,948 --> 00:36:40,742
Sure is a lot now, though, huh?

357
00:37:14,484 --> 00:37:17,154
Hey, Edward!

358
00:37:30,501 --> 00:37:32,586
I love Spectre...

359
00:37:38,509 --> 00:37:40,427
Excuse me.

360
00:37:46,517 --> 00:37:49,811
Jenny thinks you're quite a catch.
We all do.

361
00:37:51,021 --> 00:37:52,564
What?

362
00:37:52,523 --> 00:37:55,651
I said, you're quite a catch.

363
00:38:18,048 --> 00:38:19,800
I have to leave.

364
00:38:23,554 --> 00:38:24,805
Tonight.

365
00:38:25,556 --> 00:38:26,723
Why?

366
00:38:28,058 --> 00:38:30,394
This town is more than any man
could ask for.

367
00:38:31,061 --> 00:38:34,606
And if I were to end up here,
I would consider myself lucky.

368
00:38:34,565 --> 00:38:38,443
But the truth is, I'm just not ready
to end up anywhere.

369
00:38:39,069 --> 00:38:40,737
But no one's ever left.

370
00:38:42,072 --> 00:38:45,450
How are you gonna make it
without your shoes?

371
00:38:45,576 --> 00:38:48,036
Well, I suspect it will hurt. A lot.

372
00:38:52,082 --> 00:38:54,710
Now, I'm sorry, but...
Well, goodbye.

373
00:38:58,589 --> 00:39:02,092
- You won't find a better place.
- I don't expect to.

374
00:39:07,598 --> 00:39:09,266
Promise me you'll come back.

375
00:39:10,601 --> 00:39:15,397
I promise. Someday.
When I'm really supposed to.

376
00:39:46,637 --> 00:39:49,932
That night,
I reached two conclusions.

377
00:39:50,140 --> 00:39:55,062
The first was that a dangerous path
is made much worse by darkness.

378
00:39:56,146 --> 00:40:00,150
The second was that I was
hopelessly and irrevocably lost.

379
00:40:00,651 --> 00:40:03,612
These woods would become
my graveyard.

380
00:40:05,656 --> 00:40:10,536
As difficult as it was to reach Spectre,
I was fated to get there eventually.

381
00:40:11,161 --> 00:40:15,082
After all, no man can avoid
reaching the end of his life.

382
00:40:29,179 --> 00:40:33,517
And then I realized
this wasn't the end of my life.

383
00:40:33,684 --> 00:40:36,645
This isn't how I die.

384
00:40:53,704 --> 00:40:54,913
Friend.

385
00:40:55,706 --> 00:40:59,835
- What happened to your shoes?
- They kind of got ahead of me.

386
00:41:16,226 --> 00:41:19,396
I don't know if you saw it,
but Josephine had some photos...

387
00:41:19,730 --> 00:41:21,148
...in the most recent Newsweek.

388
00:41:23,734 --> 00:41:25,068
Really?

389
00:41:25,235 --> 00:41:26,612
That's just wonderful.

390
00:41:29,239 --> 00:41:33,035
I spent a week in Morocco
for the story. It was incredible.

391
00:41:33,243 --> 00:41:37,748
Oh. We'll have to pick up a copy.

392
00:41:47,758 --> 00:41:50,761
I don't know if you're aware of this,
Josephine...

393
00:41:52,262 --> 00:41:56,808
...but African parrots, in their native
Congo, they speak only French.

394
00:41:57,768 --> 00:41:58,936
Really?

395
00:41:59,770 --> 00:42:02,981
You're lucky to get four words
out of them in English.

396
00:42:03,273 --> 00:42:06,109
But if you were to walk
through the jungle...

397
00:42:06,276 --> 00:42:09,988
...you'd hear them speaking
the most elaborate French.

398
00:42:10,781 --> 00:42:15,869
Those parrots talk about everything.
Politics, movies, fashion.

399
00:42:15,786 --> 00:42:18,455
Everything but religion.

400
00:42:19,790 --> 00:42:20,999
Why not religion, Dad?

401
00:42:21,792 --> 00:42:26,255
It's rude to talk about religion. You
never know who you're gonna offend.

402
00:42:31,802 --> 00:42:34,930
Josephine actually went
to the Congo last year.

403
00:42:36,807 --> 00:42:38,767
Oh, so you know.

404
00:42:54,324 --> 00:42:56,785
Hello.

405
00:42:56,827 --> 00:42:59,079
Hi. How are you feeling?

406
00:43:00,330 --> 00:43:04,168
Oh, I was dreaming.

407
00:43:04,334 --> 00:43:07,504
What were you dreaming about?

408
00:43:07,838 --> 00:43:10,799
Oh, I don't usually remember...

409
00:43:10,841 --> 00:43:15,095
...unless they're especially portentous.
Do you know what that word means?

410
00:43:15,846 --> 00:43:18,473
It means when you dream about
something that's gonna happen.

411
00:43:19,349 --> 00:43:21,852
Like one night, I had a dream...

412
00:43:21,852 --> 00:43:26,648
...where this crow came and said:

413
00:43:26,857 --> 00:43:29,401
"Your aunt is gonna die."

414
00:43:30,861 --> 00:43:33,989
I was so scared,
I woke up my parents...

415
00:43:33,864 --> 00:43:37,993
...but they said it was just a dream
and to get back to bed.

416
00:43:38,368 --> 00:43:41,914
But the next morning,
my Aunt Stacy was dead.

417
00:43:42,372 --> 00:43:44,291
That's terrible.

418
00:43:44,374 --> 00:43:50,088
Terrible for her, but think about me,
young boy with that kind of power.

419
00:43:50,380 --> 00:43:55,052
Wasn't three weeks later when the
crow came back to me in a dream...

420
00:43:54,885 --> 00:43:59,598
...and said, "Your daddy's gonna die."

421
00:44:01,391 --> 00:44:02,851
I didn't know what to do.

422
00:44:02,893 --> 00:44:06,522
I finally told my father, but he said:

423
00:44:06,897 --> 00:44:12,694
"Oh, not to worry."
But I could see he was rattled.

424
00:44:12,903 --> 00:44:15,697
The next morning, he wasn't himself.

425
00:44:15,906 --> 00:44:20,327
Kept looking around, waiting for
something to drop on his head.

426
00:44:20,911 --> 00:44:25,916
Because the crow didn't say how it
was gonna happen, just those words:

427
00:44:25,916 --> 00:44:28,043
"Your daddy's gonna die."

428
00:44:28,919 --> 00:44:34,800
Well, he left home early
and was gone a long time.

429
00:44:34,925 --> 00:44:37,678
When he finally came back,
he looked terrible...

430
00:44:37,928 --> 00:44:41,098
...like he was waiting
for the ax to fall all day.

431
00:44:41,932 --> 00:44:43,684
He said to my mother:

432
00:44:43,934 --> 00:44:47,688
"I've just had the worst day of my life."

433
00:44:47,938 --> 00:44:51,859
"You think you've had a bad day?"
she said.

434
00:44:51,942 --> 00:44:56,989
"This morning, the milkman
dropped dead on the porch."

435
00:44:59,449 --> 00:45:03,745
Because, see, my mother
was banging the milkman.

436
00:45:05,455 --> 00:45:10,127
- Can I take your picture?
- Oh, you don't need a picture.

437
00:45:09,960 --> 00:45:14,089
Just look up the word "handsome"
in the dictionary.

438
00:45:14,464 --> 00:45:15,674
Please?

439
00:45:17,467 --> 00:45:18,969
All right.

440
00:45:22,472 --> 00:45:24,474
I have photos of the wedding
to show you.

441
00:45:24,975 --> 00:45:26,977
There is a great one
of you and my father.

442
00:45:33,483 --> 00:45:38,113
I want to see pictures of your wedding.
I've never seen any.

443
00:45:37,988 --> 00:45:41,617
That's because we didn't have
a proper wedding.

444
00:45:41,992 --> 00:45:45,245
Your mother-in-law was
never supposed to marry me.

445
00:45:45,495 --> 00:45:49,291
- She was engaged to somebody else.
- I never knew.

446
00:45:49,499 --> 00:45:52,127
Will never told you?

447
00:45:52,503 --> 00:45:54,796
Probably just as well.

448
00:45:55,005 --> 00:45:57,633
He would have told it wrong, anyway.

449
00:45:58,008 --> 00:46:01,136
All the facts, none of the flavor.

450
00:46:01,512 --> 00:46:05,182
Oh. So this is a tall tale.

451
00:46:06,016 --> 00:46:09,311
Well, it's not a short one.

452
00:46:12,022 --> 00:46:13,899
I'd just left Spectre and was
on my way to discover my destiny.

453
00:46:14,024 --> 00:46:14,650
I'd just left Spectre and was
on my way to discover my destiny.

454
00:46:15,108 --> 00:46:16,944
I'd just left Spectre and was
on my way to discover my destiny.

455
00:46:17,027 --> 00:46:19,905
Not knowing what
that would be exactly...

456
00:46:20,030 --> 00:46:24,868
...I explored every opportunity
that presented itself.

457
00:46:54,064 --> 00:46:57,818
Coco! Coco! There they are.

458
00:46:59,069 --> 00:47:02,364
Ladies and gentlemen!

459
00:47:03,073 --> 00:47:06,660
You may think
you've seen the unusual.

460
00:47:07,578 --> 00:47:12,207
You may think you've seen the bizarre.

461
00:47:13,083 --> 00:47:17,880
But I've traveled
to the five corners of the world...

462
00:47:18,088 --> 00:47:25,053
...and let me tell you,
I've never seen anything like this!

463
00:47:30,100 --> 00:47:32,060
When I met this man...

464
00:47:32,603 --> 00:47:35,272
...he was picking oranges in Florida.

465
00:47:35,105 --> 00:47:39,067
His fellow workers called him
El Penumbra. "The Shadow."

466
00:47:41,111 --> 00:47:43,572
Because when you worked
beside him...

467
00:47:44,114 --> 00:47:46,241
...he blocked out the daylight!

468
00:47:47,117 --> 00:47:51,079
Not to alarm you, ma'am,
but if this man wanted to...

469
00:47:51,622 --> 00:47:56,084
...he could crush your head
between his toes...

470
00:47:56,126 --> 00:47:59,546
...like a tiny walnut.
But he won't do it.

471
00:48:00,130 --> 00:48:02,257
No. No, ladies and gentlemen...

472
00:48:02,633 --> 00:48:04,676
...he will not hurt her...

473
00:48:05,135 --> 00:48:08,555
...because he is our own gentle giant.

474
00:48:10,140 --> 00:48:16,230
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you Colossus!

475
00:49:40,731 --> 00:49:44,359
Ladies and gentlemen,
boys and girls...

476
00:49:44,234 --> 00:49:46,528
...thank y'all for coming.

477
00:49:47,738 --> 00:49:50,616
Drive home safely, everyone.
Thank you for coming.

478
00:49:51,241 --> 00:49:54,745
It was on that night
Karl met his destiny.

479
00:49:55,746 --> 00:49:58,498
And I met mine, almost.

480
00:49:58,749 --> 00:50:03,545
They say when you meet
the love of your life, time stops.

481
00:50:03,754 --> 00:50:05,255
And that's true.

482
00:50:50,300 --> 00:50:53,345
What they don't tell you
is that once time starts again...

483
00:50:54,304 --> 00:50:57,933
...it moves extra fast to catch up.

484
00:51:30,841 --> 00:51:32,301
What's your name?

485
00:51:33,343 --> 00:51:37,222
- It's Karl.
- Karl.

486
00:51:42,853 --> 00:51:48,400
Tell me, Karl, have you ever heard
the term "involuntary servitude"?

487
00:51:48,358 --> 00:51:51,153
- No.
- "Unconscionable contract"?

488
00:51:53,363 --> 00:51:56,200
- Nope.
- Great.

489
00:51:56,366 --> 00:51:58,368
Here you go.

490
00:51:59,870 --> 00:52:01,580
Here you are.

491
00:52:04,875 --> 00:52:07,628
Mr. Soggybottom,
come down this here...

492
00:52:07,878 --> 00:52:10,047
