to sign on it.

493
00:52:22,893 --> 00:52:25,020
Okay. Thank you. Yeah.

494
00:52:26,396 --> 00:52:28,273
Hey, kid.

495
00:52:28,398 --> 00:52:31,693
- Your friend just made himself a star.
- Oh, that's great.

496
00:52:34,404 --> 00:52:36,490
- My attorney, Mr. Soggybottom.
- Good to meet you.

497
00:52:36,907 --> 00:52:38,534
Pleased to meet you.

498
00:52:43,413 --> 00:52:46,416
What's the matter? I haven't
seen a customer so depressed...

499
00:52:46,917 --> 00:52:50,212
...since the elephant sat
on that farmer's wife.

500
00:52:51,421 --> 00:52:53,507
"Depressed"?

501
00:52:55,425 --> 00:52:57,719
See? The big guy likes it.

502
00:52:58,428 --> 00:53:00,430
I just saw the woman I'm gonna marry.

503
00:53:00,430 --> 00:53:03,475
I know it. But I lost her.

504
00:53:04,935 --> 00:53:06,311
Oh, tough break.

505
00:53:06,436 --> 00:53:10,274
Well, most men have to get married
before they lose their wives.

506
00:53:10,399 --> 00:53:15,487
I'm gonna spend the rest of my life
looking for her. That or die alone.

507
00:53:15,946 --> 00:53:17,781
Damn, kid.

508
00:53:20,951 --> 00:53:23,412
Let me guess. Real pretty?

509
00:53:24,413 --> 00:53:26,290
Reddish-blondish hair?

510
00:53:28,417 --> 00:53:29,710
Blue dress?

511
00:53:30,961 --> 00:53:32,421
Yeah!

512
00:53:32,963 --> 00:53:35,924
I know her uncle. Friends of the family.

513
00:53:35,966 --> 00:53:38,093
Who is she? Where does she live?

514
00:53:38,427 --> 00:53:41,263
Forget it. Don't waste your time.
She's out of your league.

515
00:53:41,430 --> 00:53:44,808
- What? You don't even know me.
- Sure I do.

516
00:53:44,975 --> 00:53:49,479
You were hot shit back in Hickville, but
here in the real world, you got squat.

517
00:53:49,438 --> 00:53:51,398
You don't have a plan or a job.

518
00:53:51,982 --> 00:53:54,443
Nothing except the clothes
on your back.

519
00:53:54,443 --> 00:53:57,362
Well, I have a whole backpack
full of clothes.

520
00:53:58,989 --> 00:54:01,742
Oh, someone stole my backpack.

521
00:54:02,451 --> 00:54:06,413
You were a big fish in a small pond,
but this here is the ocean...

522
00:54:06,455 --> 00:54:08,916
...and you're drowning.
Go back to Puddleville.

523
00:54:09,458 --> 00:54:12,503
- You'll be happy there.
- You say I don't have a plan. I do.

524
00:54:13,003 --> 00:54:16,632
I'll find that girl, marry her,
and spend the rest of my life with her.

525
00:54:17,007 --> 00:54:20,719
I don't have a job, but I would
have a job if you gave me one.

526
00:54:21,011 --> 00:54:22,971
And I may not have much...

527
00:54:23,013 --> 00:54:26,683
...but I have more determination
than any man you're likely to meet.

528
00:54:29,019 --> 00:54:32,648
I'm sorry, kid. I don't do charity.
Come on, big boy.

529
00:54:33,482 --> 00:54:35,817
Wait. Look, I'll work
night and day for you...

530
00:54:36,485 --> 00:54:37,653
...and you won't have to pay me.

531
00:54:40,030 --> 00:54:42,991
You just have to tell me who she is.

532
00:54:46,495 --> 00:54:48,497
Every month you work for me...

533
00:54:48,497 --> 00:54:51,834
...l'll tell you one thing about her.
That's my final offer.

534
00:54:56,046 --> 00:54:58,590
Let's get started.

535
00:55:12,062 --> 00:55:15,691
From that moment on, I did everything
Mr. Calloway asked.

536
00:55:15,524 --> 00:55:18,443
I'd go three days
without stopping to eat.

537
00:55:18,527 --> 00:55:21,196
And four days without sleeping.

538
00:55:21,530 --> 00:55:24,366
What kept me going was
the promise of meeting the girl...

539
00:55:24,533 --> 00:55:25,742
...who would be my wife.

540
00:55:33,542 --> 00:55:35,878
Stick together, that's the way
it's gonna be.

541
00:55:36,086 --> 00:55:39,923
- The way it was, and the way it will be.
- Mr. Calloway, sir?

542
00:55:40,090 --> 00:55:41,633
It's been a month today.

543
00:55:44,094 --> 00:55:47,222
This girl, the love of your life...

544
00:55:48,098 --> 00:55:52,644
...her favorite flowers are daffodils.

545
00:55:53,562 --> 00:55:57,524
- So get that stuff...
- Daffodils.

546
00:55:58,567 --> 00:56:00,903
Daffodils.

547
00:56:02,571 --> 00:56:04,740
Daffodils.

548
00:56:10,579 --> 00:56:12,247
True to his word...

549
00:56:12,581 --> 00:56:15,209
...every month Amos would tell me
something new...

550
00:56:15,584 --> 00:56:17,878
...about the woman of my dreams.

551
00:56:18,128 --> 00:56:21,006
Enjoy yourselves, enjoy yourselves.

552
00:56:21,131 --> 00:56:22,674
She's going to college.

553
00:56:23,133 --> 00:56:27,304
College. She's going to college.

554
00:56:37,606 --> 00:56:38,982
She likes music.

555
00:56:39,608 --> 00:56:43,403
Music. She likes music.

556
00:56:48,158 --> 00:56:50,160
Over the months, I learned a lot
about the woman I would marry...

557
00:56:50,160 --> 00:56:52,788
Over the months, I learned a lot
about the woman I would marry...

558
00:56:52,621 --> 00:56:55,749
...but not her name,
and not where to find her.

559
00:56:55,624 --> 00:57:00,379
That time had come.
I couldn't wait any longer.

560
00:57:11,640 --> 00:57:13,851
Mr. Calloway?

561
00:57:16,186 --> 00:57:19,565
It's Edward Bloom.
I need to talk to you.

562
00:57:23,652 --> 00:57:25,988
Mr. Calloway?

563
00:58:00,230 --> 00:58:01,899
No. Wait!

564
00:58:19,708 --> 00:58:24,171
That night, I discovered that most
things you consider evil or wicked...

565
00:58:24,254 --> 00:58:28,091
...are simply lonely and lacking
in social niceties.

566
00:59:02,751 --> 00:59:04,837
Didn't kill anything, did I?

567
00:59:05,754 --> 00:59:10,092
A few rabbits. But I think one of them
was already dead.

568
00:59:13,303 --> 00:59:16,265
That would explain the indigestion.

569
00:59:23,772 --> 00:59:25,691
Thank you.

570
00:59:27,776 --> 00:59:29,611
I was wrong about you, kid.

571
00:59:29,778 --> 00:59:33,115
You may not have much,
but what you got, you got a lot of.

572
00:59:33,782 --> 00:59:36,118
You could get any girl.

573
00:59:36,326 --> 00:59:38,287
There's only one I want.

574
00:59:42,791 --> 00:59:44,042
Her name...

575
00:59:47,796 --> 00:59:49,923
...is Sandra Templeton.

576
00:59:51,800 --> 00:59:54,761
She goes to Auburn.

577
00:59:54,803 --> 00:59:59,057
Semester's almost over,
so you better hurry.

578
00:59:59,349 --> 01:00:00,851
Thank you. Thank you.

579
01:00:01,810 --> 01:00:04,229
- Good luck, kid!
- Thank you, sir!

580
01:00:16,950 --> 01:00:17,284
- Bye, now.
- Bye, Edward.

581
01:00:20,996 --> 01:00:24,333
After saying my goodbyes,
I hopped three trains...

582
01:00:24,541 --> 01:00:27,961
...to get to Auburn that afternoon.

583
01:01:03,038 --> 01:01:06,875
You don't know me,
but my name is Edward Bloom...

584
01:01:07,042 --> 01:01:08,335
...and I love you.

585
01:01:10,045 --> 01:01:13,799
I've spent the last three years
working to find out who you are.

586
01:01:14,049 --> 01:01:18,262
I've been shot, stabbed, and trampled
a few times. I broke my ribs twice.

587
01:01:18,595 --> 01:01:21,557
But it's all been worth it
to see you here now...

588
01:01:22,057 --> 01:01:25,018
...and to finally get to talk to you.

589
01:01:25,060 --> 01:01:27,354
Because I'm destined to marry you.

590
01:01:28,063 --> 01:01:34,027
I knew it when I saw you at the circus,
and I know it now more than ever.

591
01:01:36,071 --> 01:01:39,408
- I'm sorry.
- You don't have to apologize to me.

592
01:01:39,074 --> 01:01:41,493
I'm the luckiest person
you'll find today.

593
01:01:42,077 --> 01:01:45,163
No, I'm sorry I'm engaged
to be married.

594
01:01:52,087 --> 01:01:55,215
But you're wrong. I do know you.

595
01:01:55,632 --> 01:01:57,593
At least by reputation.

596
01:01:58,635 --> 01:02:01,096
Edward Bloom from Ashton.

597
01:02:01,096 --> 01:02:05,559
See, I'm actually engaged
to a boy from Ashton. Don Price.

598
01:02:06,643 --> 01:02:09,188
He was a few years older than you.

599
01:02:20,115 --> 01:02:21,491
Well...

600
01:02:24,119 --> 01:02:25,204
Congratulations.

601
01:02:28,123 --> 01:02:30,709
I'm sorry to have bothered you.

602
01:02:36,131 --> 01:02:39,176
Stop it! It's not funny.

603
01:02:40,135 --> 01:02:42,262
That poor boy.

604
01:02:42,679 --> 01:02:45,766
Fate has a cruel way
of circling around on you.

605
01:02:46,141 --> 01:02:48,143
After all this work to leave Ashton...

606
01:02:48,143 --> 01:02:53,649
...the girl I love was now engaged
to one of its biggest jerks.

607
01:02:54,149 --> 01:02:56,318
There's a time when a man
needs to fight...

608
01:02:56,151 --> 01:02:59,696
...and a time when he needs to accept
that his destiny's lost...

609
01:03:00,155 --> 01:03:04,243
...the ship has sailed,
and that only a fool will continue.

610
01:03:04,159 --> 01:03:07,371
Truth is, I've always been a fool.

611
01:03:08,705 --> 01:03:13,418
Sandra Templeton, I love you,
and I will marry you!

612
01:03:18,298 --> 01:03:18,590
So as you can see, if we apply
these rules to our everyday life...

613
01:03:22,177 --> 01:03:25,097
...supply and demand
makes much more sense.

614
01:03:25,180 --> 01:03:29,142
Take a look at the next graph, and the
import of this will be even stronger...

615
01:03:38,193 --> 01:03:40,904
- for three hours.

616
01:03:40,737 --> 01:03:42,573
Look!

617
01:04:13,729 --> 01:04:16,899
- Daffodils!
- They're your favorite flower.

618
01:04:17,232 --> 01:04:18,734
How did you get so many?

619
01:04:19,735 --> 01:04:21,320
I called everywhere in five states.

620
01:04:21,737 --> 01:04:24,698
I told them it was the only way
to get my wife to marry me.

621
01:04:26,742 --> 01:04:28,493
You don't even know me.

622
01:04:29,244 --> 01:04:31,747
I have the rest of my life to find out.

623
01:04:32,748 --> 01:04:34,416
Sandra!

624
01:04:36,752 --> 01:04:38,921
It's Don. Promise you won't hurt him.

625
01:04:38,754 --> 01:04:41,715
If that's what you want, I swear to it.

626
01:04:42,257 --> 01:04:44,593
- Bloom?
- Don.

627
01:04:45,761 --> 01:04:50,057
What the hell are you doing?
This is my girl. Mine!

628
01:04:50,265 --> 01:04:52,893
I wasn't aware
that she belonged to anyone.

629
01:04:55,771 --> 01:04:58,774
What's the matter?
Are you too scared to fight back?

630
01:04:59,274 --> 01:05:00,943
I promised I wouldn't.

631
01:05:01,777 --> 01:05:04,571
Stop it!

632
01:05:04,780 --> 01:05:05,989
Don, stop!

633
01:05:06,782 --> 01:05:11,828
While I took the beating of a lifetime,
Don Price was ultimately defeated.

634
01:05:11,787 --> 01:05:16,583
All the physical activity had worsened
a congenital valve defect.

635
01:05:16,792 --> 01:05:18,919
Put simply, his heart
wasn't strong enough.

636
01:05:31,807 --> 01:05:34,142
Don! I will never marry you.

637
01:05:34,810 --> 01:05:37,521
What?
You mean, you love this guy?

638
01:05:37,813 --> 01:05:40,941
He's almost a stranger,
and I prefer him to you.

639
01:06:09,344 --> 01:06:14,808
As it turned out, Sandra was able to
keep her same date at the chapel.

640
01:06:14,850 --> 01:06:17,978
Only the groom had changed.

641
01:06:18,854 --> 01:06:22,858
I thought you said you didn't
have a church wedding.

642
01:06:22,858 --> 01:06:25,944
We were all set to,
but there was a complication.

643
01:06:29,865 --> 01:06:33,619
Is it the medicine
that's making you thirsty?

644
01:06:34,870 --> 01:06:37,956
Truth is,
I've been thirsty my whole life.

645
01:06:38,874 --> 01:06:41,460
Never really known why.

646
01:06:42,878 --> 01:06:45,047
There was a time when I was 11...

647
01:06:44,880 --> 01:06:46,798
You were talking about your wedding.

648
01:06:47,382 --> 01:06:51,303
I didn't forget.
I was just working on a tangent.

649
01:06:51,887 --> 01:06:55,098
You see, most men, they'll tell you
a story straight through.

650
01:06:55,390 --> 01:06:59,144
It won't be complicated,
but it won't be interesting, either.

651
01:06:59,895 --> 01:07:01,271
I like your stories.

652
01:07:00,896 --> 01:07:01,396
And I like you.

653
01:07:01,897 --> 01:07:03,273
And I like you.

654
01:07:02,898 --> 01:07:03,690
Well, when you work for the circus,
you don't have a regular address.

655
01:07:04,149 --> 01:07:07,778
Well, when you work for the circus,
you don't have a regular address.

656
01:07:07,903 --> 01:07:11,031
So after three years,
there was a lot of undelivered mail.

657
01:07:11,907 --> 01:07:14,785
During the four weeks
I was in the hospital...

658
01:07:14,910 --> 01:07:17,371
...the postmaster
finally caught up with me.

659
01:07:17,412 --> 01:07:20,832
And it seems that while my heart
belonged to Sandra...

660
01:07:20,916 --> 01:07:26,588
...the rest of my body belonged
to the U.S. government.

661
01:07:43,939 --> 01:07:47,776
A hitch in the Army was up to
three years at that point...

662
01:07:47,943 --> 01:07:50,946
...and having waited three years
just to meet Sandra...

663
01:07:50,946 --> 01:07:54,908
...I knew I couldn't survive
being away from her that long.

664
01:07:54,950 --> 01:07:58,036
So I took every hazardous
assignment I could find...

665
01:07:58,453 --> 01:08:02,875
...with the hope of getting
my time down to less than a year.

666
01:08:02,958 --> 01:08:05,377
Go! Go!

667
01:08:07,963 --> 01:08:09,965
When I was offered
a secret mission...

668
01:08:09,965 --> 01:08:13,886
...to steal the plans for
the Wong Kai Tang power plant...

669
01:08:14,469 --> 01:08:17,764
...I jumped at the chance
to serve my country.

670
01:08:20,976 --> 01:08:23,145
Go! Go!

671
01:10:18,594 --> 01:10:21,138
Any of you got needs?

672
01:12:06,702 --> 01:12:08,704
How could you miss your cue?

673
01:12:09,204 --> 01:12:13,166
You make me look like a fool
out there alone.

674
01:12:13,208 --> 01:12:14,793
You weren't alone!

675
01:12:17,212 --> 01:12:18,338
Who the hell are you?

676
01:12:18,213 --> 01:12:20,007
I'm not going to hurt you.

677
01:12:20,215 --> 01:12:21,175
Damn right you're not.

678
01:12:21,717 --> 01:12:22,676
GUARD!

679
01:12:24,219 --> 01:12:25,888
Tell your men not to bother us!

680
01:12:26,221 --> 01:12:27,472
And close that curtain!

681
01:12:30,225 --> 01:12:32,311
Please, I need your help.

682
01:12:33,228 --> 01:12:35,647
What makes you think we'll help you?

683
01:12:44,239 --> 01:12:49,286
Over the next hour, I described
my love for Sandra K. Templeton...

684
01:12:49,244 --> 01:12:52,122
...and the ordeal that brought me
before them.

685
01:12:52,247 --> 01:12:55,709
As it had always been,
this love was my salvation.

686
01:12:56,251 --> 01:12:58,337
It was destined to be.

687
01:12:58,253 --> 01:13:01,340
We put together an elaborate
plan for escape...

688
01:13:01,757 --> 01:13:03,884
...involving a whaling ship
to Russia...

689
01:13:04,259 --> 01:13:08,305
...a barge to Cuba,
and a small, dirty canoe to Miami.

690
01:13:08,263 --> 01:13:11,517
We all knew it would be dangerous.

691
01:13:12,267 --> 01:13:14,645
And what are we supposed to do
when we get to America?

692
01:13:15,270 --> 01:13:16,522
I can get you bookings.

693
01:13:17,272 --> 01:13:19,608
I know the biggest man
in show business.

694
01:13:20,776 --> 01:13:21,777
Bob Hope?!

695
01:13:22,277 --> 01:13:23,237
Bigger.

696
01:13:27,282 --> 01:13:28,158
Ready?

697
01:13:31,286 --> 01:13:35,123
And so the twins and I
began our arduous journey...

698
01:13:35,290 --> 01:13:37,209
...halfway around the world.

699
01:13:37,292 --> 01:13:41,755
Unfortunately, there was no way
to send a message back to America.

700
01:13:41,797 --> 01:13:45,759
And so it was no surprise
that the Army believed I was dead.

701
01:14:02,317 --> 01:14:04,736
No, God!

702
01:14:06,321 --> 01:14:10,617
After four months, Sandra had gotten
over the worst of the nightmares.

703
01:14:11,326 --> 01:14:15,163
When the phone rang, she didn't think
it was somehow me calling her.

704
01:14:15,330 --> 01:14:20,169
When a car drove past, she didn't
get up to check out the window.

705
01:14:55,370 --> 01:14:58,457
I talked with your father last night.

706
01:15:01,877 --> 01:15:05,005
You never told me
how your parents met.

707
01:15:05,380 --> 01:15:07,341
They met at Auburn.

708
01:15:07,382 --> 01:15:11,178
What about the details?
How they fell in love.

709
01:15:11,386 --> 01:15:13,305
The circus. The war.

710
01:15:13,388 --> 01:15:15,307
You never told me any of that.

711
01:15:15,390 --> 01:15:17,476
That's because most of it
never happened.

712
01:15:19,394 --> 01:15:21,522
But it's romantic.

713
01:15:24,900 --> 01:15:27,361
- What?
- What, I know better...

714
01:15:27,903 --> 01:15:31,198
...than to argue romance
with a French woman.

715
01:15:32,407 --> 01:15:34,368
Do you love your father?

716
01:15:34,910 --> 01:15:38,539
Everyone loves my father.
He's a very likable guy.

717
01:15:39,915 --> 01:15:41,500
Do you love him?

718
01:15:46,421 --> 01:15:48,382
You have to understand.

719
01:15:48,423 --> 01:15:52,219
When I was growing up,
he was gone more than he was there.

720
01:15:52,427 --> 01:15:56,390
And I started thinking maybe he's got
this second life somewhere else.

721
01:15:57,432 --> 01:16:00,227
Another family, another house.

722
01:16:00,435 --> 01:16:03,647
And he leaves us
and goes to them.

723
01:16:03,939 --> 01:16:05,566
Or, or...

724
01:16:07,943 --> 01:16:12,406
Or maybe there is no second family.
Maybe he never wanted a family.

725
01:16:13,448 --> 01:16:17,411
Whatever it is, he likes his second life
better and he tells his stories...

726
01:16:17,953 --> 01:16:20,497
...because he can't stand
this boring place.

727
01:16:20,455 --> 01:16:23,500
- But it's not true.
- Well, what's true?

728
01:16:25,460 --> 01:16:28,255
He's never told me
a single true thing.

729
01:16:30,465 --> 01:16:31,884
Look, hey...

730
01:16:33,468 --> 01:16:36,263
I know why you like him.

731
01:16:36,471 --> 01:16:39,725
I know why everyone likes him.

732
01:16:39,975 --> 01:16:43,187
But I need you to tell me
that I'm not crazy.

733
01:16:43,478 --> 01:16:46,356
Oh, you're not.

734
01:16:48,483 --> 01:16:51,236
And I think you should talk to him.

735
01:16:56,491 --> 01:16:59,578
Larry Puckett's Chevrolet
lets the customer do the talking.

736
01:16:59,494 --> 01:17:03,207
Larry Puckett's GM-certified vehicles
are under factory warranty.

737
01:17:03,498 --> 01:17:07,503
And you can save up to 40 percent
off the original MSRP.

738
01:17:08,003 --> 01:17:10,714
- Did I ever tell you about...?
- Yes.

739
01:17:11,507 --> 01:17:15,010
The maple tree and the Buick?
We've heard it.

740
01:17:17,513 --> 01:17:21,058
I know someone who hasn't.

741
01:17:21,517 --> 01:17:24,978
- The...
- Tree fell on the car, spilling the syrup.

742
01:17:25,020 --> 01:17:28,440
Which attracted the flies,
which got stuck to it...

743
01:17:28,524 --> 01:17:31,527
...and flew off with the whole car.

744
01:17:36,532 --> 01:17:39,910
But the real story
is how I got the car.

745
01:17:40,536 --> 01:17:41,828
- You see...
- Dad?

746
01:17:42,037 --> 01:17:43,539
Son.

747
01:17:43,539 --> 01:17:45,499
Can we talk?

748
01:17:48,043 --> 01:17:50,337
I think I'll get started
on these dishes.

749
01:17:50,546 --> 01:17:52,673
I'll help you.

750
01:18:08,564 --> 01:18:11,817
- You know about icebergs, Dad?
- Do I?

751
01:18:11,567 --> 01:18:14,069
I saw an iceberg once.

752
01:18:14,570 --> 01:18:17,781
They were hauling it down to Texas
for drinking water.

753
01:18:18,073 --> 01:18:22,077
They didn't count on there being
an elephant frozen inside.

754
01:18:22,077 --> 01:18:24,705
- The woolly kind. A mammoth.
- Dad!

755
01:18:25,581 --> 01:18:27,291
What?

756
01:18:29,084 --> 01:18:31,545
I'm trying to make a metaphor here.

757
01:18:31,587 --> 01:18:34,089
Well, you shouldn't have started
with a question...

758
01:18:34,590 --> 01:18:36,300
...because people
want to answer questions.

759
01:18:36,592 --> 01:18:40,220
You should've started with,
"The thing about icebergs is..."

760
01:18:40,596 --> 01:18:43,891
Okay, okay. The thing about
icebergs is you only see 10 percent.

761
01:18:44,099 --> 01:18:47,561
The other 90 percent is below
the water where you can't see it.

762
01:18:47,603 --> 01:18:49,605
And that's...

763
01:18:49,605 --> 01:18:52,399
...what it is with you, Dad.

764
01:18:52,608 --> 01:18:55,360
I am only seeing this little bit...

765
01:18:55,611 --> 01:18:57,446
...that sticks above the water.

766
01:18:57,613 --> 01:19:00,699
Oh, you're only seeing down
to my nose? My chin? My...

767
01:19:01,116 --> 01:19:04,036
Dad, I have no idea who you are...

768
01:19:04,119 --> 01:19:07,247
...because you've never told me
a single fact.

769
01:19:07,623 --> 01:19:11,835
I've told you a thousand facts, Will.
That's what I do, I tell stories!

770
01:19:11,627 --> 01:19:15,088
You tell... lies, Dad.

771
01:19:15,631 --> 01:19:16,840
You tell amusing lies.

772
01:19:16,632 --> 01:19:19,676
Stories are what you tell
a 5-year-old at bedtime.

773
01:19:20,135 --> 01:19:22,804
They're not elaborate mythologies
that you maintain...

774
01:19:23,639 --> 01:19:25,724
...when your son is 10 and 15
and 20 and 30.

775
01:19:25,641 --> 01:19:28,519
And I believed you.

776
01:19:30,646 --> 01:19:33,982
I believed your stories
so much longer than I should have.

777
01:19:34,149 --> 01:19:37,194
Then when I realized
everything you said was impossible...

778
01:19:37,152 --> 01:19:39,279
...I felt like a fool
to have trusted you.

779
01:19:39,655 --> 01:19:41,823
You're like Santa Claus
and the Easter Bunny.

780
01:19:42,157 --> 01:19:43,992
Just as charming and just as fake.

781
01:19:44,159 --> 01:19:46,495
You think I'm fake.

782
01:19:47,663 --> 01:19:51,750
Only on the surface, Dad.
But it's all I've ever seen.

783
01:19:53,669 --> 01:19:55,379
Look.

784
01:19:56,672 --> 01:19:59,174
I'm about to have...

785
01:19:59,675 --> 01:20:00,801
...a kid of my own.

786
01:20:01,176 --> 01:20:03,720
It would kill me
if he went through his whole life...

787
01:20:04,179 --> 01:20:06,306
...never understanding me.

788
01:20:06,682 --> 01:20:08,976
It would kill you, huh?

789
01:20:10,686 --> 01:20:14,273
What do you want, Will?
Who do you want me to be?

790
01:20:14,690 --> 01:20:16,400
Just yourself.

791
01:20:16,191 --> 01:20:19,820
Good, bad, everything.
Just show me who you are for once.

792
01:20:20,195 --> 01:20:23,240
I've been nothing but myself
since the day I was born.

793
01:20:23,699 --> 01:20:28,120
And if you can't see that,
it's your failing, not mine!

794
01:20:59,234 --> 01:21:03,697
Your father decided
that he needed to have an office...

795
01:21:04,239 --> 01:21:07,618
...and, of course, it wouldn't do
to have it in the house.

796
01:21:07,743 --> 01:21:09,119
So...

797
01:21:10,746 --> 01:21:15,417
You'll know better than me
what's important.

798
01:21:25,761 --> 01:21:27,846
What is it?

799
01:21:29,264 --> 01:21:31,225
It was during the war.

800
01:21:31,266 --> 01:21:35,145
Your father went missing.
They thought he was dead.

801
01:21:36,271 --> 01:21:38,565
Oh, that really happened?

802
01:21:38,774 --> 01:21:42,569
Not everything your father says
is a complete fabrication.

803
01:21:44,279 --> 01:21:47,241
I think I'll go check on him.

804
01:21:49,785 --> 01:21:51,787
I need to lie down for a bit.

805
01:21:52,287 --> 01:21:54,915
Okay, go.

806
01:22:09,805 --> 01:22:14,726
After the war, the sons of Alabama
returned home, looking for work.

807
01:22:14,810 --> 01:22:16,603
Each had the advantage over me.

808
01:22:16,311 --> 01:22:19,773
They were alive,
while I was officially deceased.

809
01:22:20,315 --> 01:22:22,109
With my prospects few...

810
01:22:22,317 --> 01:22:26,113
...I took a job as a traveling salesman.
It suited me.

811
01:22:25,821 --> 01:22:28,907
If there was one thing
you can say about Edward Bloom...

812
01:22:29,324 --> 01:22:31,451
...it's that I am a social person.

813
01:22:32,828 --> 01:22:35,873
- Congratulations.
- Thank you, sir.

814
01:22:36,331 --> 01:22:38,792
I could be gone
for weeks at a time.

815
01:22:39,334 --> 01:22:42,254
But every other Friday,
I put all the money I made...

816
01:22:42,337 --> 01:22:45,799
...into an account set aside
for a proper house...

817
01:22:45,841 --> 01:22:48,177
...with a white picket fence.

818
01:22:53,849 --> 01:22:57,436
I'd like a moment of your time
to tell you about my new product...

819
01:22:57,853 --> 01:23:00,105
...the Handi-matic.

820
01:23:15,871 --> 01:23:19,082
A few years later, I added
other products and other cities...

821
01:23:18,874 --> 01:23:22,461
...until my territory stretched from
the coast to western Texas.

822
01:23:47,402 --> 01:23:48,779
Edward?

823
01:23:48,904 --> 01:23:50,572
Edward Bloom!

824
01:23:50,906 --> 01:23:52,574
It's me, Norther Winslow.

825
01:23:52,908 --> 01:23:54,785
I don't believe it.

826
01:23:54,910 --> 01:23:59,122
I was astonished to see the greatest
poet of both Ashton and Spectre...

827
01:23:59,414 --> 01:24:01,291
...all the way out in Texas.

828
01:24:01,416 --> 01:24:05,295
I want you to know, when you left
Spectre, it opened my eyes.

829
01:24:05,420 --> 01:24:08,924
There was a whole life out there
that I was not living.

830
01:24:08,924 --> 01:24:10,467
So I traveled.

831
01:24:10,926 --> 01:24:14,012
I saw France, Africa,
half of South America.

832
01:24:13,929 --> 01:24:16,598
Every day, a new adventure.
That's my motto.

833
01:24:16,932 --> 01:24:19,017
That's great, Norther.
I'm happy for you.

834
01:24:19,434 --> 01:24:21,812
What are you doing now?

835
01:24:22,938 --> 01:24:24,398
I'm robbing this place.

836
01:24:28,443 --> 01:24:30,195
All right, everybody down!

837
01:24:31,947 --> 01:24:35,158
Hey!
Just slide that over.

838
01:24:41,456 --> 01:24:44,251
- Would you mind grabbing that?
- What?

839
01:24:44,960 --> 01:24:45,836
The gun.

840
01:24:47,963 --> 01:24:49,798
I'm gonna be cleaning out
the cash drawers...

841
01:24:49,965 --> 01:24:54,094
...and my associate here
is gonna handle the vault.

842
01:25:00,475 --> 01:25:03,979
All right, you!
You help my friend, okay?

843
01:25:04,479 --> 01:25:06,023
Let's go!

844
01:25:26,001 --> 01:25:27,920
I'm sorry, ma'am.
I am.

845
01:25:28,003 --> 01:25:31,089
I really just don't want anyone
to get hurt.

846
01:25:31,507 --> 01:25:33,425
It's not that.

847
01:25:34,009 --> 01:25:35,969
It's just...

848
01:25:41,517 --> 01:25:42,976
There's no money.

849
01:25:44,019 --> 01:25:47,898
We're completely bankrupt.
Don't tell anybody.

850
01:25:48,023 --> 01:25:51,985
It turned out that the Savings & Loan
had already been robbed...

851
01:25:52,027 --> 01:25:56,615
...not by armed bandits, but
by speculators in Texas real estate.

852
01:25:57,032 --> 01:25:58,992
All right, let's go!

853
01:26:10,045 --> 01:26:12,047
Norther!

854
01:26:31,567 --> 01:26:34,361
Yeah! There's gotta be
close to $400 here!

855
01:26:34,570 --> 01:26:36,989
And that's just from the drawers.

856
01:26:37,072 --> 01:26:39,616
Let's see what you got
from the vault.

857
01:26:49,585 --> 01:26:52,045
This is it? The whole vault?

858
01:26:52,588 --> 01:26:55,048
I'm afraid so.

859
01:26:58,093 --> 01:26:59,761
It's got your deposit slip on it.

860
01:26:59,595 --> 01:27:01,555
Well, I just didn't want you
leaving empty-handed.

861
01:27:02,598 --> 01:27:06,185
There's something you should know.
The reason they don't have money...

862
01:27:06,602 --> 01:27:09,771
I told Norther about
the vagaries of Texas oil money...

863
01:27:10,105 --> 01:27:12,983
...and its effect on real-estate prices...

864
01:27:13,108 --> 01:27:16,195
...and how lax enforcement
of fiduciary process...

865
01:27:16,612 --> 01:27:20,407
...had made savings and loans
particularly vulnerable.

866
01:27:20,616 --> 01:27:25,412
Hearing this news,
Norther was left with one conclusion:

867
01:27:25,621 --> 01:27:29,082
I should go to Wall Street.
That's where all the money is.

868
01:27:29,124 --> 01:27:32,586
I knew then that while my days
as a criminal were over...

869
01:27:32,628 --> 01:27:33,795
Thanks for the hand!

870
01:27:34,129 --> 01:27:36,089
...Norther's were just beginning.

871
01:27:36,131 --> 01:27:38,634
When Norther made
his first million dollars...

872
01:27:38,634 --> 01:27:40,844
...he sent me a check for 10,000.

873
01:27:41,136 --> 01:27:45,182
I protested, but he said it was my fee
as his career advisor.

874
01:27:45,641 --> 01:27:49,061
It was enough to buy my wife
a proper house...

875
01:27:49,144 --> 01:27:51,104
...with a white picket fence.

876
01:27:51,146 --> 01:27:55,275
And for that, it was all the riches
a man could ever want.

877
01:28:29,184 --> 01:28:31,103
I was drying out.

878
01:28:32,688 --> 01:28:35,107
I see.

879
01:28:37,192 --> 01:28:41,321
I think we ought to get you
a plant mister...

880
01:28:41,196 --> 01:28:43,991
...so we can just spray you
like a fern.

881
01:29:10,225 --> 01:29:12,561
Come, now.

882
01:29:16,732 --> 01:29:20,027
I don't think I'll ever dry out.

883
01:30:18,293 --> 01:30:21,255
You carry on. I'll see...

884
01:30:26,301 --> 01:30:28,095
Hello.

885
01:30:28,303 --> 01:30:32,224
- Are you Jennifer Hill?
- I am.

886
01:30:32,307 --> 01:30:34,601
And you're Will.

887
01:30:34,810 --> 01:30:37,771
I've seen a picture of you.
That's how I recognize you.

888
01:30:40,315 --> 01:30:43,026
Listen, Kenny,
why don't we skip the lesson today?

889
01:30:43,318 --> 01:30:45,529
We can go again next week.

890
01:30:45,821 --> 01:30:47,781
Do I have to give it back to my mom?

891
01:30:48,323 --> 01:30:50,742
Well, I won't tell her if you won't.

892
01:31:01,920 --> 01:31:03,255
How did you know my father?

893
01:31:04,006 --> 01:31:06,049
Well, this was on his sales route...

894
01:31:06,008 --> 01:31:10,012
...so he was through here all the time,
and everyone in town knew him.

895
01:31:10,512 --> 01:31:12,514
Were you having an affair?

896
01:31:15,017 --> 01:31:17,311
Wow. Wow, you just said it.

897
01:31:18,020 --> 01:31:21,732
I was expecting to dance
around this for another half-hour.

898
01:31:23,525 --> 01:31:26,528
I've seen him with women.
He flirts. He always has.

899
01:31:27,029 --> 01:31:31,241
And on some level,
I just presumed that he was...

900
01:31:31,033 --> 01:31:34,411
...cheating on my mom.
I just never had proof.

901
01:31:37,539 --> 01:31:39,416
Well, can I ask you a question?

902
01:31:39,541 --> 01:31:42,336
If you found this deed,
why didn't you just ask Eddie?

903
01:31:43,045 --> 01:31:45,297
Because he's dying.

904
01:31:54,556 --> 01:31:59,394
Look, I don't know how much
you want to know about any of this.

905
01:31:59,061 --> 01:32:01,104
You have one image of your father...

906
01:32:01,563 --> 01:32:03,774
...and it'd be wrong of me
to change it...

907
01:32:04,066 --> 01:32:05,651
...especially this late in the game.

908
01:32:06,068 --> 01:32:08,362
My father talked about things
he never did...

909
01:32:08,570 --> 01:32:12,157
...and I'm sure he did a lot of things
that he never talked about.

910
01:32:12,074 --> 01:32:14,034
I'm just trying to reconcile the two.

911
01:32:17,579 --> 01:32:20,666
The first thing
you have to understand...

912
01:32:21,083 --> 01:32:23,877
...is that your father
never meant to end up here.

913
01:32:24,586 --> 01:32:25,879
Yet he did.

914
01:32:26,088 --> 01:32:27,631
Twice.

915
01:32:28,090 --> 01:32:30,509
The first time, he was early.

916
01:32:31,093 --> 01:32:33,095
The second time, he was late.

917
01:32:35,097 --> 01:32:39,017
Those days, your father was working
for himself.

918
01:32:39,101 --> 01:32:42,020
If there's one thing you could
say about Edward Bloom...

919
01:32:42,604 --> 01:32:47,568
...it's that he was a social person,
and people took a liking to him.

920
01:32:47,609 --> 01:32:50,737
One night, he was returning
from three weeks on the road...

921
01:32:51,613 --> 01:32:54,658
...when he hit a thunderstorm
unlike any in his life.

922
01:34:43,225 --> 01:34:45,602
Fate has a way of circling back
on a man...

923
01:34:45,727 --> 01:34:47,771
...and taking him by surprise.

924
01:34:52,734 --> 01:34:56,405
A man sees things differently
at different times in his life.

925
01:34:56,238 --> 01:35:00,200
This town didn't seem the same
now that he was older.

926
01:35:01,743 --> 01:35:05,330
A new road had brought
the outside world to Spectre...

927
01:35:05,247 --> 01:35:08,333
...and with it, banks, liens and debt.

928
01:35:08,750 --> 01:35:13,547
Almost everywhere you looked,
people were bankrupt.

929
01:35:14,756 --> 01:35:18,051
The auction today
is for the town of Spectre.

930
01:35:18,260 --> 01:35:20,846
- The opening bid will be $ 10,000.
- So Edward Bloom...

931
01:35:21,263 --> 01:35:23,599
...decided to buy the town.
- 50,000.

932
01:35:27,769 --> 01:35:31,106
- I couldn't believe my eyes...
- He was never a wealthy man...

933
01:35:31,273 --> 01:35:36,403
...but he had made other men rich,
and now he asked for their favors.

934
01:35:38,280 --> 01:35:41,241
- I'm trying to save...
- Most of them hadn't seen Spectre.

935
01:35:41,783 --> 01:35:44,953
They only had Edward's words
to describe it.

936
01:35:44,786 --> 01:35:48,165
That's all he needed.
He sold them on the dream.

937
01:35:48,790 --> 01:35:51,502
So first he bought the farms.

938
01:35:51,293 --> 01:35:55,172
Then he bought the houses.
And then he bought the stores.

939
01:35:55,797 --> 01:36:00,844
Whatever he bought, the people were
not asked to leave or pay rent.

940
01:36:01,303 --> 01:36:04,014
They were just asked to keep
doing as they were doing.

941
01:36:04,306 --> 01:36:08,268
In that way, he could make sure
the town would never die.

942
01:36:10,812 --> 01:36:16,193
Within six months, his trust had
purchased the entire town.

943
01:36:16,318 --> 01:36:18,862
With one exception.

944
01:36:43,345 --> 01:36:46,348
You must be Edward Bloom.

945
01:36:46,348 --> 01:36:47,516
How do you know?

946
01:36:48,350 --> 01:36:50,936
No one would come out here
unless they had business.

947
01:36:51,353 --> 01:36:54,189
And no one would have business
with me except for you.

948
01:36:54,356 --> 01:36:56,608
You're buying the town.

949
01:36:57,860 --> 01:37:01,864
Apparently I overlooked this one
piece of it, and I'd like to remedy that.

950
01:37:01,864 --> 01:37:06,702
In order for the town to be preserved,
the trust must own it, in its entirety.

951
01:37:06,869 --> 01:37:08,328
And so I've heard.

952
01:37:08,370 --> 01:37:11,707
I'll offer you more than it's worth.
And you won't have to move.

953
01:37:11,874 --> 01:37:15,377
Nothing will change except the name
on the deed, you have my word.

954
01:37:15,878 --> 01:37:18,589
Now, let me get this straight.

955
01:37:18,380 --> 01:37:21,216
You buy the swamp from me,
but I'll stay in it?

956
01:37:21,383 --> 01:37:23,886
You'll own the house,
but it'll still be mine?

957
01:37:24,386 --> 01:37:28,223
I'll be here, and you'll come and go as
you please to one place or another.

958
01:37:28,390 --> 01:37:30,309
Do I have that right?

959
01:37:30,392 --> 01:37:32,853
In so many words, yes.

960
01:37:33,896 --> 01:37:35,856
Yeah, then I don't think so,
Mr. Bloom.

961
01:37:36,899 --> 01:37:39,860
If nothing's gonna change,
I'd just as soon it not change...

962
01:37:39,902 --> 01:37:42,863
...in the way things haven't been
changing all this time.

963
01:37:43,906 --> 01:37:48,702
It's not like you'll lose anything.
You can ask anyone in town.

964
01:37:50,412 --> 01:37:52,623
Why are you buying this land,
Mr. Bloom?

965
01:37:52,915 --> 01:37:54,499
Some sort of midlife crisis?

966
01:37:55,417 --> 01:37:57,878
Instead of buying a convertible,
you buy a town?

967
01:37:58,420 --> 01:38:00,506
Helping people makes me happy.

968
01:38:01,423 --> 01:38:04,510
I'm not convinced
you should be happy.

969
01:38:04,927 --> 01:38:08,889
- I'm sorry. Have I offended you?
- No.

970
01:38:08,931 --> 01:38:10,849
You did exactly what you promised.

971
01:38:11,433 --> 01:38:15,896
You came back.
I was just expecting you sooner.

972
01:38:23,445 --> 01:38:24,905
You're Beamen's daughter.

973
01:38:26,949 --> 01:38:29,701
Your name's different.
Did you get married?

974
01:38:30,452 --> 01:38:35,499
I was 18. He was 28.
Turns out that was a big difference.

975
01:38:44,967 --> 01:38:48,804
I won't be selling you this house,
Mr. Bloom.

976
01:38:49,471 --> 01:38:51,014
I see.

977
01:38:51,974 --> 01:38:55,394
Well, thank you for your time.

978
01:39:05,487 --> 01:39:08,574
- It's stuck.
- Yeah.

979
01:39:19,001 --> 01:39:22,045
- Oh, I'm so sorry! l...
- It's okay. Just leave it.

980
01:39:22,504 --> 01:39:24,840
- No, I'll...
- Please! Just go.

981
01:39:26,508 --> 01:39:28,802
- But...
- Go.

982
01:39:31,013 --> 01:39:35,809
Most men in that situation would
accept their failure and move on.

983
01:39:36,018 --> 01:39:38,061
But Edward was not like most men.

984
01:39:38,020 --> 01:39:38,562
But Edward was not like most men.

985
01:39:48,530 --> 01:39:49,865
Hold!

986
01:39:54,036 --> 01:39:56,163
They both had completely
different characters but...

987
01:39:57,039 --> 01:39:59,082
...well, just one pair of legs.

988
01:40:09,551 --> 01:40:12,971
As the months passed, he found
more and more things to fix...

989
01:40:13,055 --> 01:40:16,934
...until the shack no longer
resembled itself.

990
01:40:33,075 --> 01:40:37,287
Of course, the best part
was coming up with the new material.

991
01:40:38,080 --> 01:40:40,624
By the time the twins and I
had got to Havana...

992
01:40:40,582 --> 01:40:46,255
...we'd worked out a new routine,
using only a ukulele and a harmonica.

993
01:41:05,607 --> 01:41:09,069
- Well...
- You could leave it there.

994
01:41:26,628 --> 01:41:28,088
No.

995
01:41:38,640 --> 01:41:40,392
Now, don't.

996
01:41:41,143 --> 01:41:45,731
Don't be embarrassed. I should never
have let you think that...

997
01:41:47,149 --> 01:41:49,276
I'm in love with my wife.

998
01:41:50,152 --> 01:41:52,112
Yeah, I know.

999
01:41:52,654 --> 01:41:55,449
And from the first day I saw her
until the day I die...

1000
01:41:55,657 --> 01:41:57,701
...she's the only one.

1001
01:41:58,660 --> 01:42:01,121
Lucky girl.

1002
01:42:01,663 --> 01:42:04,833
I'm sorry, Jenny. I am.

1003
01:42:12,174 --> 01:42:14,593
Wait! Edward.

1004
01:42:56,218 --> 01:42:59,137
One day, Edward Bloom left...

1005
01:42:59,221 --> 01:43:03,058
...and never returned
to the town he'd saved.

1006
01:43:15,737 --> 01:43:17,698
As for the girl...

1007
01:43:17,739 --> 01:43:20,242
...the common belief
was that she'd become a witch...

1008
01:43:21,243 --> 01:43:23,036
...and crazy at that.

1009
01:43:24,246 --> 01:43:27,749
She became something
of a legend herself.

1010
01:43:29,251 --> 01:43:34,006
And the story ended where it began.

1011
01:43:34,756 --> 01:43:37,801
Logically, you couldn't be
the witch, because she was...

1012
01:43:37,759 --> 01:43:38,927
...old when he was young.

1013
01:43:39,261 --> 01:43:42,556
Well, it's logical if you think
like your father.

1014
01:43:43,265 --> 01:43:47,144
See, to him there's only
two women:

1015
01:43:47,769 --> 01:43:49,229
Your mother...

1016
01:43:49,271 --> 01:43:50,939
...and everyone else.

1017
01:43:50,772 --> 01:43:52,649
And one day...

1018
01:43:53,275 --> 01:43:57,613
...I realized I was in love with a man
who could never love me back.

1019
01:43:58,280 --> 01:44:01,241
I was living in a fairy tale.

1020
01:44:01,783 --> 01:44:04,036
I'm not sure I should've told you
any of this.

1021
01:44:04,286 --> 01:44:06,872
No, no, no, I wanted to know. I'm...

1022
01:44:07,289 --> 01:44:08,624
I'm glad I know.

1023
01:44:09,291 --> 01:44:12,544
I wanted to be as important to him
as you were.

1024
01:44:13,295 --> 01:44:15,088
And I'm...

1025
01:44:15,297 --> 01:44:17,716
I was never gonna be.

1026
01:44:20,302 --> 01:44:21,887
I was make-believe.

1027
01:44:23,305 --> 01:44:28,227
And his other life, you...

1028
01:44:28,310 --> 01:44:29,895
You were real.

1029
01:44:54,336 --> 01:44:55,963
Mom?

1030
01:44:56,839 --> 01:44:58,674
Josephine?

1031
01:45:00,843 --> 01:45:02,261
Josephine?

1032
01:45:16,358 --> 01:45:18,402
Will!

1033
01:45:19,361 --> 01:45:20,737
What happened?

1034
01:45:20,863 --> 01:45:22,447
Your father had a stroke.

1035
01:45:23,365 --> 01:45:25,951
He's upstairs with your mom
and Dr. Bennett.

1036
01:45:25,868 --> 01:45:27,119
Is he gonna be okay?

1037
01:45:35,377 --> 01:45:37,421
I don't suppose that I could...

1038
01:45:37,379 --> 01:45:39,923
...stay here with him.
I mean, in case...

1039
01:45:40,883 --> 01:45:43,802
In case he wakes up,
I really ought to be here.

1040
01:45:43,886 --> 01:45:45,095
I'll stay.

1041
01:45:46,388 --> 01:45:49,349
Why don't you go home with
Josephine. I'll stay tonight.

1042
01:45:51,393 --> 01:45:54,354
- Is that okay?
- Fine.

1043
01:45:56,899 --> 01:45:59,818
Will, you'll call if there's any...?

1044
01:46:00,402 --> 01:46:03,488
I will. I will. I'll call.

1045
01:46:04,907 --> 01:46:08,869
- Do you want some time with Dad?
- Yes. Thank you.

1046
01:47:12,975 --> 01:47:16,395
Glad to see you're not trying
to have a heartfelt talk.

1047
01:47:19,481 --> 01:47:22,067
One of my greatest
annoyances is when...

1048
01:47:22,484 --> 01:47:25,404
...people try to talk to those
who can't hear them.

1049
01:47:25,487 --> 01:47:27,573
Well, we have an advantage.

1050
01:47:27,990 --> 01:47:30,075
My father and I never talk.

1051
01:47:36,999 --> 01:47:40,085
Your father ever tell you
about the day you were born?

1052
01:47:40,002 --> 01:47:43,297
Yeah, a thousand times.
He caught an uncatchable fish.

1053
01:47:43,505 --> 01:47:47,467
Not that. The real story.
He ever tell you that?

1054
01:47:48,010 --> 01:47:49,636
No.

1055
01:47:50,012 --> 01:47:53,348
Well, your mother came in about
3 in the afternoon.

1056
01:47:53,515 --> 01:47:58,187
Her neighbor drove her, on account of
your father was away on business...

1057
01:47:58,020 --> 01:47:59,479
...in Wichita.

1058
01:48:00,522 --> 01:48:04,276
You were born a week early,
but there were no complications.

1059
01:48:04,526 --> 01:48:10,240
It was a perfect delivery.
Your father was sorry not to be there.

1060
01:48:10,532 --> 01:48:15,287
But it wasn't the custom then for men
to be in the room for deliveries...

1061
01:48:15,537 --> 01:48:19,708
...so I can't see how it would've been
much different had he been there.

1062
01:48:20,042 --> 01:48:22,628
And that's the real story
of how you were born.

1063
01:48:23,545 --> 01:48:25,839
Not very exciting, is it?

1064
01:48:26,048 --> 01:48:29,927
And I suppose if I had to choose
between the true version...

1065
01:48:30,052 --> 01:48:34,473
...and an elaborate one involving
a fish and a wedding ring...

1066
01:48:34,556 --> 01:48:36,517
...I might choose the fancy version.

1067
01:48:37,559 --> 01:48:39,520
But, then that's just me.

1068
01:48:40,562 --> 01:48:42,564
I kind of liked your version.

1069
01:49:04,586 --> 01:49:06,213
Dad?

1070
01:49:08,090 --> 01:49:11,552
Hey, Dad? Hey, you want me
to get the nurse?

1071
01:49:13,595 --> 01:49:16,640
What do you want? What can I do?
What can I get?

1072
01:49:17,099 --> 01:49:19,476
You want some water?

1073
01:49:20,102 --> 01:49:21,520
You want a bit of water?

1074
01:49:24,606 --> 01:49:27,359
The river.

1075
01:49:28,610 --> 01:49:30,487
The river?

1076
01:49:31,113 --> 01:49:35,200
Tell me how it happens.

1077
01:49:37,119 --> 01:49:39,997
How what happens?

1078
01:49:40,122 --> 01:49:42,457
How I go.

1079
01:49:46,628 --> 01:49:49,173
You mean what you saw in The Eye?

1080
01:50:03,145 --> 01:50:06,398
I don't know that story, Dad.
You never told me that one.

1081
01:50:09,651 --> 01:50:12,654
Okay. Hey, okay, I'll try.

1082
01:50:12,654 --> 01:50:15,282
I need your help.
Tell me how it starts.

1083
01:50:17,659 --> 01:50:21,330
Like this.

1084
01:50:21,663 --> 01:50:23,665
Okay. Okay.

1085
01:50:26,168 --> 01:50:29,505
Okay, so it's in the morning...

1086
01:50:29,671 --> 01:50:33,717
...and you and I are in the hospital,
and I've fallen asleep. And I wake up...

1087
01:50:34,176 --> 01:50:37,471
...and I see you,
and somehow you're better.

1088
01:50:38,180 --> 01:50:39,348
Dad?

1089
01:50:39,181 --> 01:50:41,141
You're different.

1090
01:50:42,184 --> 01:50:45,145
- Dad.
- Let's get out of here.

1091
01:50:45,187 --> 01:50:46,396
Then I say:

1092
01:50:46,688 --> 01:50:48,190
Dad, you're in no condition...

1093
01:50:48,190 --> 01:50:50,484
Get that wheelchair.

1094
01:50:53,195 --> 01:50:55,239
Hurry up! We haven't much time!

1095
01:50:55,197 --> 01:50:57,491
Once we get off this floor,
we're in the clear.

1096
01:50:57,699 --> 01:50:59,409
And we get in the wheelchair...

1097
01:50:59,701 --> 01:51:03,163
- Faster!
...like we're escaping the hospital.

1098
01:51:03,205 --> 01:51:05,165
What are you doing?

1099
01:51:05,207 --> 01:51:07,417
We pass Dr. Bennett,
who tries to slow us down.

1100
01:51:07,709 --> 01:51:10,671
- Stop them!
- We're flying down the hall.

1101
01:51:10,712 --> 01:51:12,673
Orderly after orderly is chasing us.

1102
01:51:13,215 --> 01:51:15,133
Mom and Josephine
are at the end.

1103
01:51:15,217 --> 01:51:18,178
No time to explain! Stall them!

1104
01:51:23,725 --> 01:51:25,686
We come flying out
over the curb...

1105
01:51:25,727 --> 01:51:30,190
...and your old red Charger is there.
But it's new. Brand-new.

1106
01:51:30,732 --> 01:51:32,985
And I pick you up...

1107
01:51:32,734 --> 01:51:36,405
...and somehow you hardly weigh
anything. I can't explain it.

1108
01:51:40,742 --> 01:51:43,495
Leave it! We don't need it!

1109
01:51:45,747 --> 01:51:48,208
Water. I need water.

1110
01:51:51,253 --> 01:51:53,213
- Where are we going?
- The river.

1111
01:52:00,262 --> 01:52:02,639
And we have to take Glenville
to avoid traffic...

1112
01:52:02,764 --> 01:52:05,559
...because the damn church
people drive too slow.

1113
01:52:46,808 --> 01:52:51,980
And as we get close to the river...

1114
01:53:00,322 --> 01:53:02,449
He's here!

1115
01:53:02,824 --> 01:53:05,661
...we see that everybody
is already there.

1116
01:53:22,344 --> 01:53:23,804
And I mean...

1117
01:53:25,347 --> 01:53:26,515
...everyone.

1118
01:53:38,861 --> 01:53:41,613
It's unbelievable.

1119
01:53:42,364 --> 01:53:47,119
The story of my life.

1120
01:53:54,877 --> 01:53:57,796
The strange thing is, there's
not a sad face to be found.

1121
01:53:57,880 --> 01:54:00,465
Everyone is just so glad
to see you...

1122
01:54:01,884 --> 01:54:04,094
...and send you off right.

1123
01:54:03,886 --> 01:54:09,516
Goodbye, everybody!
Farewell! Adieu!

1124
01:54:20,903 --> 01:54:23,488
My girl in the river.

1125
01:55:34,977 --> 01:55:37,813
You become what you always were.

1126
01:55:39,481 --> 01:55:41,775
A very big fish.

1127
01:55:46,989 --> 01:55:49,408
And that's how it happens.

1128
01:55:50,993 --> 01:55:52,786
Yeah.

1129
01:55:55,497 --> 01:55:57,666
Exactly.

1130
01:56:40,042 --> 01:56:41,752
Mom?

1131
01:58:08,630 --> 01:58:11,800
The Lord is my shepherd,
I shall not be in want.

1132
01:58:12,134 --> 01:58:15,888
He makes me to lie down
in green pastures.

1133
01:58:15,637 --> 01:58:18,557
He leads me beside the quiet waters.

1134
01:58:18,640 --> 01:58:20,601
He restores my soul.

1135
01:58:21,143 --> 01:58:25,105
He guides me in the paths of
righteousness for his name's sake.

1136
01:58:25,647 --> 01:58:28,817
Yea, though I walk through
the valley of the shadow of death...

1137
01:58:29,151 --> 01:58:31,820
...I will fear no evil,
for you are with me.

1138
01:58:31,653 --> 01:58:35,908
Surely goodness and love will
follow me all the days of my life.

1139
01:59:23,205 --> 01:59:27,835
Have you ever heard a joke so many
times you've forgotten why it's funny?

1140
01:59:27,709 --> 01:59:31,713
And then you hear it again
and suddenly it's new.

1141
01:59:32,214 --> 01:59:35,300
You remember why you loved it
in the first place.

1142
01:59:37,219 --> 01:59:40,305
So he said he'll fight the giant
who was 15 feet tall!

1143
01:59:40,222 --> 01:59:43,684
- No way!
- Dad! That's right, isn't it?

1144
01:59:44,226 --> 01:59:45,477
Pretty much.

1145
01:59:45,727 --> 01:59:47,855
See? So he was a giant.

1146
01:59:47,729 --> 01:59:50,107
That was my father's final joke,
I guess.

1147
01:59:50,732 --> 01:59:56,488
A man tells his stories so many times
that he becomes the stories.

1148
01:59:57,739 --> 01:59:59,992
They live on after him.

1149
02:00:02,744 --> 02:00:05,998
And in that way,
he becomes immortal.


1150
02:00:05,998 --> 02:04:05,998
Sub by -- Gladiator
